Does Iran still have the means to retaliate against the US and Israel?
description: The salvos of missiles fired at Israel have become less frequent, a likely sign of Tehran's weakening position. Iran could still activate its allies, notably the Houthi movement, although the Houthis have so far upheld their ceasefire with Washington.

Refusing to become a manager is more common in France than elsewhere
description: According to an international survey by Cegos, a significant share of employees showed little interest in becoming managers, especially in France. The reasons include organizational culture, the image of the managerial role and the emergence of alternative models of professional success.

headline: Paris Olympics and Paralympics cost taxpayers nearly €6 billion
description: The organization of the two sporting extravaganzas last summer cost €2.77 billion, which included €1.4 billion for security. A further €3.19 billion was spent on work linked to infrastructure projects.

headline: Finding inspiration for photography in the kitchen
description: From Irving Penn's frozen fruits and vegetables to Sabine Weiss's fish trap and the Blumes' flying crockery, kitchens, their utensils, and their ingredients have long inspired photographers. Striking images by some 30 artists add spice to the exhibition 'Dans ma cuisine' ('In My Kitchen'), on view through July 31 at Les Douches gallery in Paris.

headline: Trump's balancing act: Promising peace while striking Iran
description: Faced with opposition from some within his own party and Americans wary of another potential conflict, the US president insisted he acted 'to stop the war.' Yet he now faces the likelihood of having to deal with reprisals against US troops in the Middle East.

headline: Unpacking the tech bros' fascination with the Roman Empire
description: Silicon Valley's top executives are almost all captivated by the Roman Empire and its decline. Their obsession shapes how they see the world.

headline: The Heritage Foundation sets its sights on Europe
description: Since the beginning of his term, Donald Trump has been applying Project 2025, a 922-page bible written by the conservative think tank. Today, its president, Kevin Roberts, is looking across the Atlantic. On a visit to France, he met with leaders of far-right parties.
